# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: combustor
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:combustor/accessory-drive] The **accessory drive** is a gearbox that forms part of a gas turbine engine.
[src:combustor/accessory-drive] Although not part of the engine's core, it drives the accessories – such as generators, pumps for fuel and lubrication oil, air compressors, hydraulic pumps and engine starters – that are otherwise essential for the operation of the engine or the aircraft on which it is mounted.
[src:combustor/accessory-drive] Accessory drives on large engines handle between 400–500 hp.
[src:combustor/accessory-drive] Power for the accessory drive is taken from the central shaft linking the turbine and compressor sections of the engine.
[src:combustor/accessory-drive] This requires an internal gearbox that couples the drive to a radial driveshaft or *towershaft* that drives an external gearbox.
[src:combustor/accessory-drive] The design of the internal gearbox is complicated by the heat and small space available in which to connect the driveshaft.
[src:combustor/accessory-drive] It is usually placed between the compressor outlet and the combustor.
[src:combustor/accessory-drive] In turboprops or designs with centrifugal compressors, it may be placed ahead of the compressor.
[src:combustor/accessory-drive] For two-shaft designs, an accessory drive will be taken from the high-pressure shaft, i.e. the outer and shorter of the two concentric shafts.
[src:combustor/accessory-drive] This shaft comes up to speed more quickly when the engine is started.
[src:combustor/accessory-drive] The drive and accessory gearboxes may also be split in two, one driven from each engine shaft, so as to distribute their loads.
[src:combustor/accessory-drive] The engine-critical systems, including the starter drive, are arranged on the high-pressure shaft, with aircraft systems on the low-pressure shaft.
[src:combustor/accessory-drive] The high-pressure shaft also rotates faster than the low-pressure shaft, which may influence the distribution of accessories.
[src:combustor/accessory-drive] To make the best use of the limited space for the driveshaft and internal gearbox, the driveshaft runs at high speed, thus allowing it to be of small diameter.
[src:combustor/accessory-drive] This reduces the disruption to the airflow and the size of the hollow fairing that encloses it.
[src:combustor/accessory-drive] If it is not possible to arrange a single straight path for the driveshaft, it may be arranged in two sections and linked by an intermediate gearbox.
[src:combustor/accessory-drive] This is most commonly required for high-bypass turbofans with large diameter fans.
[src:combustor/accessory-drive] The packaging of an engine within its nacelle is a complicated task.
[src:combustor/accessory-drive] The accessory drive is usually arranged as a curved casing, so that the various accessories are mounted close to the engine.
[src:combustor/accessory-drive] The casing is a pair of light alloy castings.
[src:combustor/accessory-drive] Separate machined mounting pads are provided for each accessory.
[src:combustor/accessory-drive] The drive within the casing is provided by a train of spur gears.
[src:combustor/accessory-drive] Accessories are arranged on both sides of the driveshaft entry, in reducing order of their speed.
[src:combustor/accessory-drive] The gears are usually plain spur gears, running in roller bearings.
[src:combustor/accessory-drive] Idler gears are commonly used between them, to increase the spacing between accessories.
[src:combustor/accessory-drive] Helical gears are sometimes used for the high-torque drives, typically the starter, as these give smoother running.
[src:combustor/accessory-drive] However helical gears also generate an end-thrust, which then requires a more complicated thrust bearing to support them.
[src:combustor/accessory-drive] The complexity of an accessory drive and its gears is so great that they were used as a theme by the anthropomorphic illustrator Boris Artzybasheff in advertising for the Avco Lycoming company, who were making drive gearboxes for the Westinghouse J40 engine.
[src:combustor/accessory-drive] In some engines, bleed air is also tapped to provide power for accessories, as well as a mechanical shaft drive.
[src:combustor/accessory-drive] Bleed air is particularly useful when a source of compressed air is specifically needed, either to pressurise cabin air, or as a supply of cooling air to other components (to avoid excess heat, this is taken for a low-pressure tapping, or from the LP compressor of a two-shaft engine).
[src:combustor/accessory-drive] One important use for bleed air is for cross-starting of other engines in a multi-engine aircraft.
[src:combustor/accessory-drive] Additional facilities are provided for a centrifugal oil breather, to separate the drive lubricating oil from the overboard breather air vent.
[src:combustor/accessory-drive] Also access for hand-turning the engine, during ground maintenance.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] Modern aerial warfare includes missiles and unmanned aerial vehicles.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] Surface forces are likely to respond to enemy air activity with anti-aircraft warfare.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] The history of aerial warfare began in ancient times, with the use of man-carrying kites in Ancient China.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] In the third century it progressed to balloon warfare.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] Airships (notably zeppelins) served in military use in the early years of the 20th century.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] Heavier-than-air airplanes first went to war in the Italo-Turkish War in 1911, initially for aerial reconnaissance, and then for aerial combat to shoot down enemy reconnaissance planes.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] Aircraft continued to carry out these roles during World War I (1914-1918), where the use of planes and zeppelins for strategic bombing also emerged.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] The rise of fighter aircraft and of air-to-air combat led to a realisation of the desirability of achieving air superiority.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] Closer integration of attacking aircraft with ground operations ("battlefield support") also developed during World War I.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] During World War II (1939-1945), the use of strategic bombing increased, while airborne forces, missiles, and early precision-guided munitions were introduced.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] Aircraft carriers gained particular importance in the trans-oceanic projection of air power.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] Ballistic missiles became of key importance during the Cold War, were armed with nuclear warheads, and were stockpiled by the United States and the Soviet Union to deter each other from using them.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] Drone warfare using relatively cheap unmanned equipment proliferated in the 21st century, particularly after the start of the Second Nagorno-Karabakh War in 2020.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] Aerial reconnaissance is reconnaissance for a military or strategic purpose that is conducted using reconnaissance aircraft.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] This role can fulfil a variety of requirements, including the collection of imagery intelligence, observation of enemy maneuvers and artillery spotting.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] Air combat manoeuvring (also known as ACM or dogfighting) is the tactical art of moving, turning and situating a fighter aircraft in order to attain a position from which an attack can be made on another aircraft.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] It relies on offensive and defensive basic fighter manoeuvring (BFM) to gain an advantage over an aerial opponent.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] Airborne forces are military units, usually light infantry, set up to be moved by aircraft and "dropped" into battle, typically by parachute.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] Thus, they can be placed behind enemy lines, and have the capability to deploy almost anywhere with little warning.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] The formations are limited only by the number and size of their aircraft, so given enough capacity a huge force can appear "out of nowhere" in minutes, an action referred to as *vertical envelopment*.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] Conversely, airborne forces typically lack the supplies and equipment for prolonged combat operations, and are therefore more suited for airhead operations than for long-term occupation; furthermore, parachute operations are particularly sensitive to adverse weather conditions.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] Advances in helicopter technology since World War II have brought increased flexibility to the scope of airborne operations, and air assaults have largely replaced large-scale parachute operations, and (almost) completely replaced combat glider operations.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] An airstrike or *air strike* is an offensive operation carried out by attack aircraft.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] Air strikes are mostly delivered from aircraft such as fighters, bombers, ground attack aircraft, and attack helicopters.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] The official definition includes all sorts of targets, including enemy air targets, but in popular use the term is usually narrowed to a tactical (small-scale) attack on a ground or naval objective.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] Weapons used in an airstrike can range from machine gun bullets and missiles to various types of bombs.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] It is also commonly referred to as an *air raid*.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] In close air support, air strikes are usually controlled by trained observers for coordination with friendly ground troops in a manner derived from artillery tactics.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] Strategic bombing is a military strategy used in a total war with the goal of defeating the enemy by destroying their morale or their economic ability to produce and transport materiel to the theatres of military operations, or both.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] It is a systematically organized and executed attack from the air which can utilize strategic bombers, long- or medium-range missiles, or nuclear-armed fighter-bomber aircraft to attack targets deemed vital to the enemy's war-making capability.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] It may be used to protect naval, ground, and air forces in any location.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] However, for most countries the main effort has tended to be 'homeland defence'.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] NATO refers to airborne air defence as *counter-air* and naval air defence as *anti-aircraft warfare*.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] Missile defence is an extension of air defence as are initiatives to adapt air defence to the task of intercepting any projectile in flight.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] In modern usage, a missile is a self-propelled precision-guided munition system, as opposed to an unguided self-propelled munition, referred to as a rocket (although these too can also be guided).
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] Missiles have four system components: targeting and/or missile guidance, flight system, engine, and warhead.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] Missiles come in types adapted for different purposes: surface-to-surface and air-to-surface missiles (ballistic, cruise, anti-ship, anti-tank, etc.), surface-to-air missiles (and anti-ballistic), air-to-air missiles, and anti-satellite weapons.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] All known existing missiles are designed to be propelled during powered flight by chemical reactions inside a rocket engine, jet engine, or other type of engine.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] Non-self-propelled airborne explosive devices are generally referred to as shells and usually have a shorter range than missiles.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] In ordinary British-English usage predating guided weapons, a missile is "any thrown object", such as objects thrown at players by rowdy spectators at a sporting event.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] The advent of the unmanned aerial vehicle has dramatically revolutionised aerial warfare with multiple nations developing and/or purchasing UAV fleets.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] UAVs have quickly evolved from surveillance to combat roles.
[src:combustor/aerial-combat] The growing capability of UAVs has thrown into question the survivability and capability of manned fighter jets.
[src:combustor/afterburner] An **afterburner** (or **reheat** in British English) is an additional combustion component used on some jet engines, mostly those on military supersonic aircraft.
[src:combustor/afterburner] Its purpose is to increase thrust, usually for supersonic flight, takeoff, and combat.
[src:combustor/afterburner] The afterburning process injects additional fuel into a combustor ("burner") in the jet pipe behind (i.e., "after") the turbine, "reheating" the exhaust gas.
[src:combustor/afterburner] Afterburning significantly increases thrust and is used as an alternative to a larger, heavier engine.
[src:combustor/afterburner] However, it increases fuel consumption and decreases fuel efficiency, which limits its use to short periods.
[src:combustor/afterburner] This aircraft application of "reheat" contrasts with the meaning and implementation of "reheat" applicable to gas turbines driving electrical generators and which reduces fuel consumption.
[src:combustor/afterburner] Jet engines are referred to as operating *wet* when afterburning and *dry* when not.
[src:combustor/afterburner] An engine producing maximum thrust wet is at *maximum power,* while an engine producing maximum thrust dry is at *military power*.
[src:combustor/afterburner] The first jet engine with after-burner was the E variant of the Jumo 004.
[src:combustor/afterburner] Jet-engine thrust is an application of Newton's reaction principle, in which the engine generates thrust because it increases the momentum of the air passing through it.
[src:combustor/afterburner] Thrust depends on two things: the velocity of the exhaust gas and the mass of the gas exiting the nozzle.
[src:combustor/afterburner] A jet engine can produce more thrust by either accelerating the gas to a higher velocity or ejecting a greater mass of gas from the engine.
[src:combustor/afterburner] Designing a basic turbojet engine around the second principle produces the turbofan engine, which creates slower gas, but more of it.
[src:combustor/afterburner] Turbofans are highly fuel efficient and can deliver high thrust for long periods of time, but the design tradeoff is a large size relative to the power output.
[src:combustor/afterburner] Generating increased power with a more compact engine for short periods can be achieved using an afterburner.
[src:combustor/afterburner] The afterburner increases thrust primarily by accelerating the exhaust gas to a higher velocity.
[src:combustor/afterburner] The following values and parameters are for an early jet engine, the Pratt & Whitney J57, stationary on the runway, and illustrate the high values of afterburner fuel flow, gas temperature and thrust compared to those for the engine operating within the temperature limitations for its turbine.
[src:combustor/afterburner] The highest temperature in the engine (about 3,700 °F (2,040 °C) occurs in the combustion chamber, where fuel is burned (at an approximate rate of 8,520 lb/h (3,860 kg/h)) in a relatively small proportion of the air entering the engine.
[src:combustor/afterburner] The combustion products have to be diluted with air from the compressor to bring the gas temperature down to a specific value, known as the Turbine Entry Temperature (TET) (1,570 °F (850 °C)), which gives the turbine an acceptable life.
[src:combustor/afterburner] Having to reduce the temperature of the combustion products by a large amount is one of the primary limitations on how much thrust can be generated (10,200 lbf (45,000 N)).
[src:combustor/afterburner] The gas temperature decreases as it passes through the turbine (to 1,013 °F (545 °C)).
[src:combustor/afterburner] The afterburner combustor reheats the gas, but to a much higher temperature (2,540 °F (1,390 °C)) than the TET (1,570 °F (850 °C)).
[src:combustor/afterburner] As a result of the temperature rise in the afterburner combustor, the gas is accelerated, firstly by the heat addition, known as Rayleigh flow, then by the nozzle to a higher exit velocity than that which occurs without the afterburner.
[src:combustor/afterburner] The mass flow is also slightly increased by the addition of the afterburner fuel.
[src:combustor/afterburner] The thrust with afterburning is 16,000 lbf (71,000 N).
[src:combustor/afterburner] The visible exhaust may show *shock diamonds*, which are caused by shock waves formed due to slight differences between ambient pressure and the exhaust pressure.
[src:combustor/afterburner] This interaction causes oscillations in the exhaust jet diameter over a short distance and causes visible banding where pressure and temperature are highest.
[src:combustor/afterburner] Thrust may be increased by burning fuel in a turbofan's cold bypass air, instead of the mixed cold and hot flows as in most afterburning turbofans.
[src:combustor/afterburner] An early augmented turbofan, the Pratt & Whitney TF30, used separate burning zones for the bypass and core flows with three of seven concentric spray rings in the bypass flow.
[src:combustor/afterburner] In comparison, the afterburning Rolls-Royce Spey used a twenty chute mixer before the fuel manifolds.
[src:combustor/afterburner] Plenum chamber burning (PCB) was partially developed for the vectored thrust Bristol Siddeley BS100 engine for the Hawker Siddeley P.1154 until the program was cancelled in 1965.
[src:combustor/afterburner] The cold bypass and hot core flows were split between two pairs of nozzles, front and rear, in the same manner as the Rolls-Royce Pegasus, and fuel was burned in the fan air before it left the front nozzles.
[src:combustor/afterburner] It would have given greater thrust for take-off and supersonic performance in an aircraft similar to, but bigger than, the Hawker Siddeley Harrier.
[src:combustor/afterburner] Duct heating was used by Pratt & Whitney for their JTF17 turbofan proposal for the U.S.
[src:combustor/afterburner] Supersonic Transport Program in 1964 and a demonstrator engine was run.
[src:combustor/afterburner] The duct heater used an annular combustor and would be used for takeoff, climb and cruise at Mach 2.7 with different amounts of augmentation depending on aircraft weight.
[src:combustor/afterburner] A jet engine afterburner is an extended exhaust section containing extra fuel injectors.
[src:combustor/afterburner] Since the jet engine upstream (i.e., before the turbine) will use little of the oxygen it ingests, additional fuel can be burned after the gas flow has left the turbines.
[src:combustor/afterburner] When the afterburner is turned on, fuel is injected and igniters are fired.
[src:combustor/afterburner] The resulting combustion process increases the afterburner exit (nozzle entry) temperature, resulting in a significant increase in engine thrust.
[src:combustor/afterburner] The resulting increase in afterburner exit volume flow is accommodated by increasing the throat area of the exit nozzle.
[src:combustor/afterburner] Otherwise, if pressure is not released, the gas can flow upstream and re-ignite, possibly causing a compressor stall (or fan surge in a turbofan application).
[src:combustor/afterburner] Solar afterburners used on the F7U Cutlass, F-94 Starfire and F-89 Scorpion, had 2-position eyelid nozzles.
[src:combustor/afterburner] Modern designs incorporate not only variable-geometry (VG) nozzles but multiple stages of augmentation via separate spray bars.
[src:combustor/afterburner] To a first order, the gross thrust ratio (afterburning/dry) is directly proportional to the root of the stagnation temperature ratio across the afterburner (i.e. exit/entry).
[src:combustor/afterburner] Due to their high fuel consumption, afterburners are only used for short-duration, high-thrust requirements.
[src:combustor/afterburner] These include heavy-weight or short-runway take-offs, assisting catapult launches from aircraft carriers, and during air combat.
[src:combustor/afterburner] A notable exception is the Pratt & Whitney J58 engine used in the SR-71 Blackbird which used its afterburner for prolonged periods and was refueled in-flight as part of every reconnaissance mission.
[src:combustor/afterburner] An afterburner has a limited life to match its intermittent use.
[src:combustor/afterburner] The J58 was an exception with a continuous rating.
[src:combustor/afterburner] This was achieved with thermal barrier coatings on the liner and flame holders and by cooling the liner and nozzle with compressor bleed air instead of turbine exhaust gas.
[src:combustor/afterburner] In heat engines such as jet engines, efficiency is highest when combustion occurs at the highest pressure and temperature possible, and expanded down to ambient pressure (see Carnot cycle).
[src:combustor/afterburner] Since the exhaust gas already has a reduced oxygen content, owing to previous combustion, and since the fuel is not burning in a highly compressed air column, the afterburner is generally inefficient in comparison to the main combustion process.
[src:combustor/afterburner] Afterburner efficiency also declines significantly if, as is usually the case, the inlet and tailpipe pressure decreases with increasing altitude.
[src:combustor/afterburner] This limitation applies only to turbojets.
[src:combustor/afterburner] In a military turbofan combat engine, the bypass air is added into the exhaust, thereby increasing the core and afterburner efficiency.
[src:combustor/afterburner] In turbojets the gain is limited to 50%, whereas in a turbofan it depends on the bypass ratio and can be as much as 70%.
[src:combustor/afterburner] However, as a counterexample, the SR-71 had reasonable efficiency at high altitude in afterburning ("wet") mode owing to its high speed (Mach 3.2) and correspondingly high pressure due to ram intake.
[src:combustor/afterburner] Afterburning has a significant influence upon engine cycle choice.
[src:combustor/afterburner] Lowering the fan pressure ratio decreases specific thrust (both dry and wet afterburning), but results in a lower temperature entering the afterburner.
[src:combustor/afterburner] Since the afterburning exit temperature is effectively fixed, the temperature rise across the unit increases, raising the afterburner fuel flow.
[src:combustor/afterburner] The total fuel flow tends to increase faster than the net thrust, resulting in a higher specific fuel consumption (SFC).
[src:combustor/afterburner] However, the corresponding dry power SFC improves (i.e. lower specific thrust).
[src:combustor/afterburner] The high temperature ratio across the afterburner results in a good thrust boost.
[src:combustor/afterburner] If the aircraft burns a large percentage of its fuel with the afterburner alight, it pays to select an engine cycle with a high specific thrust (i.e. high fan pressure ratio/low bypass ratio).
[src:combustor/afterburner] The resulting engine is relatively fuel efficient with afterburning (i.e.
[src:combustor/afterburner] Combat/Take-off), but thirsty in dry power.
[src:combustor/afterburner] If, however, the afterburner is to be hardly used, a low specific thrust (low fan pressure ratio/high bypass ratio) cycle will be favored.
[src:combustor/afterburner] Such an engine has a good dry SFC, but a poor afterburning SFC at Combat/Take-off.
[src:combustor/afterburner] Often the engine designer is faced with a compromise between these two extremes.
[src:combustor/afterburner] The Caproni Campini C.C.2 motorjet, designed by the Italian engineer Secondo Campini, was the first aircraft to incorporate an afterburner.
[src:combustor/afterburner] The first flight of a C.C.2, with its afterburners operating, took place on 11 April 1941.
[src:combustor/afterburner] Early British afterburner ("reheat") work included flight tests on a Rolls-Royce W2/B23 in a Gloster Meteor I in late 1944 and ground tests on a Power Jets W2/700 engine in mid-1945.
[src:combustor/afterburner] This engine was destined for the Miles M.52 supersonic aircraft project.
[src:combustor/afterburner] Early American research on the concept was done by NACA, in Cleveland, Ohio, leading to the publication of the paper "Theoretical Investigation of Thrust Augmentation of Turbojet Engines by Tail-pipe Burning" in January 1947.
[src:combustor/afterburner] American work on afterburners in 1948 resulted in installations on early straight-wing jets such as the Pirate, Starfire and Scorpion.
[src:combustor/afterburner] The new Pratt & Whitney J48 turbojet, at 8,000 lbf (36 kN) thrust with afterburners, would power the Grumman swept-wing fighter F9F-6, which was about to go into production.
[src:combustor/afterburner] Other new Navy fighters with afterburners included the Chance Vought F7U-3 Cutlass, powered by two 6,000 lbf (27 kN) thrust Westinghouse J46 engines.
[src:combustor/afterburner] In the 1950s, several large afterburning engines were developed, such as the Orenda Iroquois and the British de Havilland Gyron and Rolls-Royce Avon RB.146 variants.
[src:combustor/afterburner] The Avon and its variants powered the English Electric Lightning, the first supersonic aircraft in RAF service.
[src:combustor/afterburner] The Bristol-Siddeley/Rolls-Royce Olympus was fitted with afterburners for use with the BAC TSR-2.
[src:combustor/afterburner] This system was designed and developed jointly by Bristol-Siddeley and Solar of San Diego.
[src:combustor/afterburner] The afterburner system for the Concorde was developed by Snecma.
[src:combustor/afterburner] Afterburners are generally used only in military aircraft, and are considered standard equipment on fighter aircraft.
[src:combustor/afterburner] The handful of civilian planes that have used them include some NASA research aircraft, the Tupolev Tu-144, Concorde and the White Knight of Scaled Composites.
[src:combustor/afterburner] Concorde flew long distances at supersonic speeds.
[src:combustor/afterburner] Sustained high speeds would be impossible with the high fuel consumption of afterburner, and the plane used afterburners at takeoff and to minimize time spent in the high-drag transonic flight regime.
[src:combustor/afterburner] Supersonic flight without afterburners is referred to as supercruise.
[src:combustor/afterburner] A turbojet engine equipped with an afterburner is called an "afterburning turbojet", whereas a turbofan engine similarly equipped is sometimes called an "augmented turbofan".
[src:combustor/afterburner] A "dump-and-burn" is an airshow display feature where fuel is jettisoned, then intentionally ignited using the afterburner.
[src:combustor/afterburner] A spectacular flame combined with high speed makes this a popular display for airshows, or as a finale to fireworks.
[src:combustor/afterburner] Fuel dumping is used primarily to reduce the weight of an aircraft to avoid a heavy, high-speed landing.
[src:combustor/afterburner] Other than for safety or emergency reasons, fuel dumping does not have a practical use.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] An **air-start system** is a power source used to provide the initial rotation to start large diesel engines and gas turbines.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] Compared to a gasoline (petrol) engine, a diesel engine has a very high compression ratio, an essential design feature, as it is the heat of compression that ignites the fuel.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] An electric starter with sufficient power to turn a large diesel engine would itself be so large as to be impractical so there is a need for an alternative system.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] An air start system has three main components along with various safety components, namely the air start injector, the distributor and the air receivers.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] When the system is initiated, starting air from the receivers is distributed by the distributor unit to each respective air start valve according to the firing order of the engine’s cylinders.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] Safety components include flame traps, to prevent air line explosions, a turning gear interlock which ensures that air-start cannot be initiated when the turning gear is engaged, relief valves and isolation valves, as well as drain valves at certain points along the system.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] Control components include the control valves and remote air-start valves.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] A direct start system as used on a marine slow-speed diesel is required to have up to 12 starts on a non-reversing engine or 6 starts on a reversible, or geared, engine.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] When starting the engine, compressed air is admitted to whichever cylinder has a piston just over top dead center, forcing it downward.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] As the engine starts to turn, the air-start valve on the next cylinder in line opens to continue the rotation.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] After several rotations, fuel is injected into the cylinders, the engine starts running and the air is cut off.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] To further complicate matters, a large engine is usually "blown over" first with zero fuel settings and the indicator cocks open, to prove that the engine is clear of any water build up and that everything is free to turn.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] After a successful blow ahead and a blow astern, the indicator cocks are closed on all the cylinders, and then the engine can be started on fuel.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] Significant complexity is added to the engine by using an air-start system, as the cylinder head must have an extra valve in each cylinder to admit the air in for starting, plus the required control systems.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] This added complexity and cost limits the use of air-starters to very large and expensive reciprocating engines.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] Another method of air-starting an internal combustion engine is by using compressed air or gas to drive a fluid motor in place of an electric motor.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] They can be used to start engines from 5 to 320 liters in size and if more starting power is necessary two or more motors can be used.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] Starters of this type are used in place of electric motors because of their lighter weight and higher reliability.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] They can also outlast an electric starter by a factor of three and are easier to rebuild.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] Engines operating in underground mining activities tend to operate on this type of starter system to reduce the risk of an electrical system igniting flammable material.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] All vane type air starters should have a lubricator installed to insure long-life and maximum performance.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] Lubricators give the moving parts a needed friction barrier, reduce metal corrosion and keep vanes sealed properly against the cylinder walls.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] Even the so-called lube-free air starters require lubrication to prolong trouble free life.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] Two basic lubricator devices are typically employed.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] One is an in-line or reservoir type that typically stores up to 2 quarts of lubricant, and is installed along the air supply line.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] The second style of lubricator is a small one shot device that dispenses a measured amount of lubricant every time the starter is engaged.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] Installed directly onto the air inlet of the starter, the in-line lubricators are self priming pneumatic pumps that require a 1/4″ lubrication line piped from as far away as 4 feet.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] Air Starter lubricators perform best using misting type, non-detergent oils such as diesel fuel or Marvel Mystery oil.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] If emissions are a concern, there are environmentally friendly type lubricants available on the market.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] Not all air starters require lubrication.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] Turbine type air starters do not require air motor lubrication, although some turbine air starters do use an oil filled transmission that may require periodic inspections and maintenance.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] Compressed air has been used to start gas turbine engines using air impingement starting (in which air is directed at the engine turbine blades through nozzles in the turbine casing, used on US Navy General Electric J79 engines).
[src:combustor/air-start-system] It is much more efficient to use an air turbine starter (ATS) which is usually mounted on an accessory gearbox.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] An early axial compressor turbojet had an ATS located in the compressor nose cone (eg particular variants of the J79).
[src:combustor/air-start-system] Air impingement starting was not used for US military aircraft after the F-4B, A-5A and F-5 as the pneumatic energy requirement was several times greater than when using an air turbine starter.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] The gas turbine compressor required to start a J79 with impingement starting was sufficient to start two J79 engines simultaneously in a B-58 when using air turbine starters.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] An ATS has its own turbine and gears to change its low torque and high speed to low speed and high torque at the engine mounting pad.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] Further gears in the engine gearbox connect to the engine shaft (high pressure spool on multi-spool engines).
[src:combustor/air-start-system] Compared with electric starters, air-starters have a higher power-to-weight ratio so are used on large engines as an electric starter would be too big and, with its cables, too heavy and expensive.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] However, for smaller engines, which don't need as much starter power, an electric starter is more suitable.
[src:combustor/air-start-system] It has a dual function as a generator (is known as a starter/generator) at speeds above which the engine no longer requires starter assistance.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] The **air turborocket** is a form of combined-cycle jet engine.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] The basic layout includes a gas generator, which produces high pressure gas, that drives a turbine/compressor assembly which compresses atmospheric air into a combustion chamber.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] This mixture is then combusted before leaving the device through a nozzle and creating thrust.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] There are many different types of air turborockets.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] The various types generally differ in how the gas generator section of the engine functions.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] Air turborockets are often referred to as **turboramjets**, **turboramjet rockets**, **turborocket expanders**, and many others.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] As there is no consensus on which names apply to which specific concepts, various sources may use the same name for two different concepts.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] The benefit of this setup is increased specific impulse over that of a rocket.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] For the same carried mass of propellant as a rocket motor, the overall output of the air turborocket is much higher.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] In addition, it provides thrust throughout a much wider speed range than a ramjet, yet is much cheaper and easier to control than a gas turbine engine.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] The air turborocket fills a niche (in terms of cost, reliability, ruggedness, and duration of thrust) between the solid-fuel rocket motor and gas turbine engine for missile applications.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] A **turborocket** is a type of aircraft engine combining elements of a jet engine and a rocket.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] It typically comprises a multi-stage fan driven by a turbine, which is driven by the hot gases exhausting from a series of small rocket-like motors mounted around the turbine inlet.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] The turbine exhaust gases mix with the fan discharge air, and combust with the air from the compressor before exhausting through a convergent-divergent propelling nozzle.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] Once a jet engine goes high enough in an atmosphere, there is insufficient oxygen to burn the jet fuel.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] The idea behind a turborocket is to supplement the atmospheric oxygen with an onboard supply.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] This allows operation at a much higher altitude than a normal engine would allow.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] The turborocket design offers a mixture of benefits with drawbacks.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] It is not a true rocket, so it cannot operate in space.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] Cooling the engine is not a problem because the burner and its hot exhaust gases are located behind the turbine blades.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] The air turboramjet engine is a combined cycle engine that merges aspects of turbojet and ramjet engines.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] The turboramjet is a hybrid engine that essentially consists of a turbojet mounted inside a ramjet.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] The turbojet core is mounted inside a duct that contains a combustion chamber downstream of the turbojet nozzle.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] The turboramjet can be run in turbojet mode at takeoff and during low-speed flight but then switch to ramjet mode to accelerate to high Mach numbers.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] The operation of the engine is controlled using bypass flaps located just downstream of the diffuser.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] During low-speed flight, controllable flaps close the bypass duct and force air directly into the compressor section of the turbojet.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] During high-speed flight, the flaps block the flow into the turbojet, and the engine operates like a ramjet using the *aft* combustion chamber to produce thrust.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] The engine would start out operating as a turbojet during takeoff and while climbing to altitude.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] Upon reaching high subsonic speed, the portion of the engine downstream of the turbojet would be used as an afterburner to accelerate the plane above the speed of sound.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] At lower speeds, air passes through an inlet and is then compressed by an axial compressor.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] That compressor is driven by a turbine, which is powered by hot, high-pressure gas from a combustion chamber.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] These initial aspects are very similar to how a turbojet operates, however, there are several differences.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] The first is that the combustor in the turboramjet is often separate from the main airflow.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] Instead of combining air from the compressor with fuel to combust, the turboramjet combustor may use hydrogen and oxygen, carried on the aircraft, as its fuel for the combustor.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] The air compressed by the compressor bypasses the combustor and turbine section of the engine, where it is mixed with the turbine exhaust.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] The turbine exhaust can be designed to be fuel-rich (i.e., the combustor does not burn all the fuel) which, when mixed with the compressed air, creates a hot fuel-air mixture which is ready to burn again.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] More fuel is injected into this air where it is again combusted.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] The exhaust is ejected through a propelling nozzle, generating thrust.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] Picture shown lacks required bypass ducting around the compressor for ramjet operation.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] Shown is a low bypass turbojet with re-heat.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] The turboramjet engine is used when space is constrained, as it takes up less space than separate ramjet and turbojet engines.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] Since a ramjet must already be traveling at high speeds before it will start working, a ramjet-powered aircraft is incapable of taking off from a runway under its own power; that is the advantage of the turbojet, which is a member of the gas turbine family of engines.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] A turbojet does not rely purely on the motion of the engine to compress the incoming air flow; instead, the turbojet contains some additional rotating machinery that compresses incoming air and allows the engine to function during takeoff and at slow speeds.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] In applications which stay relatively in the atmosphere and require longer durations of lower thrust over a specific speed range the air turborocket can have a weight advantage over the standard solid fuel rocket motor.
[src:combustor/air-turborocket] In terms of volumetric requirements, the rocket motor has the advantage due to the lack of inlet ducts and other air management devices.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine-controls] *Right* - The left magneto p-lead is grounded, and the right is open.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine-controls] This disables the left magneto and enables the right magneto only.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine-controls] *Left* - The right magneto p-lead is grounded, and the left is open.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine-controls] This disables the right magneto and enables the left magneto only.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine-controls] *Both* - This is the normal operating configuration, both p-leads are open, enabling both magnetos.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine-controls] *Start* - The pinion gear on the starter motor is engaged with the flywheel and the starter motor runs to turn the engine over.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine-controls] In most cases, only the left magneto is active (the right p-lead is grounded) due to timing differences between the magnetos at low RPMs.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine-controls] In an aircraft with a **fixed-pitch propeller**, there is no direct control over the propeller rotational speed, which depends on the airspeed and loading.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine-controls] Therefore, the pilot has to pay attention to the RPM indicator and adjust the throttle/power lever in order to maintain the desired constant speed of the propeller.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine-controls] For example, when the airspeed reduces and the loading increases (e.g., in a climb), RPM will decrease and the pilot has to increase the throttle/power.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine-controls] When the airspeed increases and the loading decreases (e.g., in a dive), the RPM will increase and the pilot has to decrease the throttle/power in order to prevent RPM from exceeding the operational limits and damaging the motor.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine-controls] Restricting the volume of cooling airflow too much.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine-controls] Insufficient delivery of lubricating oil to the engine's moving parts.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] An **aircraft engine**, often referred to as an **aero engine**, is the power component of an aircraft propulsion system.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] Aircraft using power components are referred to as **powered flight**.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] Most aircraft engines are either piston engines or gas turbines, although a few have been rocket powered and in recent years many small UAVs have used electric motors.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] The market for aircraft engines, especially jet engines, has very high barriers to entry.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] Aircraft engines use highly advanced technology and materials, take around eight years and billions of dollars or euros to develop, and must pass exacting safety certifications by aviation safety authorities.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] Consequently, entering the engine market is extremely capital- and time-intensive, which helps protect existing manufacturers from competition.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] The last successful entry in the global market for jet engines was General Electric in the 1970s.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] These barriers to entry make the market very lucrative for existing manufacturers.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] As of 2025, the leading jet engine manufacturers reported shareholder returns from between 100 and 1,000 percent over the last five years, compared to small or negative returns for their principal clients, Airbus and Boeing.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] The engines themselves are typically sold at a loss, but manufacturers derive their profits from the sale of maintenance services and spare parts over the roughly thirty-year lifespan of an engine, following the razor and blades business model.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] This creates a perverse incentive for manufacturers to slow the production or delay the delivery of new engines, because they profit most from the use of old engines, which need more service and spare parts than new ones.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] This contributed to the unavailability of new engines, creating a bottleneck for Airbus and Boeing's efforts to increase aircraft production in the post-COVID resurgence of aviation after 2023.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] A radial engine has the cylinders placed in a circle around the crankshaft.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] The engine is air-cooled, which can be a problem since they may overheat.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] Compared to liquid-cooled engines, radial engines have the advantage of being more rugged and capable of absorbing damage.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] Rotating radial engines have the cylinders in a circle around the crankcase, as in a radial engine, (see above), but the crankshaft is fixed to the airframe and the propeller is fixed to the engine case, so that the crankcase and cylinders rotate.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] The advantage of this arrangement is that a satisfactory flow of cooling air is maintained even at low airspeeds, retaining the weight advantage and simplicity of a conventional air-cooled engine without one of their major drawbacks.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] The first practical rotary engine was the Gnome Omega designed by the Seguin brothers and first flown in 1909.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] Its relative reliability and good power to weight ratio changed aviation dramatically.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] The Wankel engine is about one half the weight and size of a traditional four-stroke cycle piston engine of equal power output, and much lower in complexity.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] In an aircraft application, the power-to-weight ratio is very important, making the Wankel engine a good choice.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] Because the engine is typically constructed with an aluminium housing and a steel rotor, and aluminium expands more than steel when heated, a Wankel engine does not seize when overheated, unlike a piston engine.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] This is an important safety factor for aeronautical use.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] Considerable development of these designs started after World War II, but at the time the aircraft industry favored the use of turbine engines.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] It was believed that turbojet or turboprop engines could power all aircraft, from the largest to smallest designs.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] The Wankel engine did not find many applications in aircraft, but was used by Mazda in a popular line of sports cars.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] The French company Citroën had developed Wankel powered RE-2 helicopter in 1970's.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] In modern times the Wankel engine has been used in motor gliders where the compactness, light weight, and smoothness are crucially important.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] Starting in the 1930s, attempts were made to produce a practical aircraft diesel engine.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] In general, Diesel engines are more reliable and much better suited to running for long periods of time at medium power settings.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] Improvements in Diesel technology in automobiles (leading to much better power-weight ratios), the Diesel's much better fuel efficiency, and the high relative taxation of AVGAS compared to Jet A1 in Europe have all seen a revival of interest in the use of diesels for aircraft.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] Thielert Aircraft Engines converted Mercedes Diesel automotive engines, certified them for aircraft use, and became an OEM provider to Diamond Aviation for their light twin.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] Financial problems have plagued Thielert, so Diamond's affiliate — Austro Engine — developed the new AE300 turbodiesel, also based on a Mercedes engine.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] A turboprop consists of an intake, reduction gearbox, compressor, combustor, turbine, and a propelling nozzle.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] Air enters the intake and is compressed by the compressor.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] Jet fuel is then added to the compressed air in the combustor, where it then combusts.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] The hot combustion gases expand through the turbine stages, generating power at the point of exhaust.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] Some of the power generated by the turbine is used to drive the compressor and electric generator.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] The gases are then exhausted from the turbine, but do not provide enough power to create a major portion of the total thrust, since almost all of the engine's power is used to drive the propeller.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] A **turboshaft** engine is a form of gas turbine that is optimized to produce shaft horsepower rather than jet thrust.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] The engine has two major parts assemblies: the 'gas generator' and the 'power section'.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] The gas generator consists of the compressor, combustion chambers with ignitors and fuel nozzles, and one or more stages of turbine.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] The power section consists of additional stages of turbines, a gear reduction system, and the shaft output.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] The gas generator creates the hot expanding gases to drive the power section; the engine accessories may be driven either by the gas generator or by the power section.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] A number of electrically powered aircraft, such as the QinetiQ Zephyr, have been designed since the 1960s.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] In France in late 2007, a conventional light aircraft powered by an 18 kW electric motor using lithium polymer batteries was flown, covering more than 50 kilometers (31 mi), the first electric airplane to receive a certificate of airworthiness.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] On 18 May 2020, the Pipistrel E-811 was the first electric aircraft engine to be awarded a type certificate by EASA for use in general aviation.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] The E-811 powers the Pipistrel Velis Electro.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] Many big companies, such as Siemens, are developing high-performance electric engines for aircraft use; also, SAE shows new developments in elements as pure Copper core electric motors with a better efficiency.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] A hybrid system as emergency back-up and for added power in take-off is offered for sale by Axter Aerospace, Madrid, Spain.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] The term *advanced technology engine* refers to the modern generation of jet engines.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] A rocket turbine engine is a combination of two types of propulsion engines: a liquid-propellant rocket and a turbine jet engine.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] Its power-to-weight ratio is a little higher than a regular jet engine, and it works at higher altitudes.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] At the April 2018 ILA Berlin Air Show, Munich-based research institute de:Bauhaus Luftfahrt presented a high-efficiency composite cycle engine for 2050, combining a geared turbofan with a piston engine core.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] The 11,200 lb (49.7 kN) engine could power a 50-seat regional jet.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] Its cruise TSFC would be 11.5 g/kN/s (0.406 lb/lbf/hr) for an overall engine efficiency of 48.2%, for a burner temperature of 1,700 K (1,430 °C), an overall pressure ratio of 38 and a peak pressure of 30 MPa (300 bar).
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] Although engine weight increases by 30%, aircraft fuel consumption is reduced by 15%.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] Sponsored by the European Commission under Framework 7 project LEMCOTEC, Bauhaus Luftfahrt, MTU Aero Engines and GKN Aerospace presented the concept in 2015, raising the overall engine pressure ratio to over 100 for a 15.2% fuel burn reduction compared to 2025 engines.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] On multi-engine aircraft, engine positions are numbered from left to right from the point of view of the pilot looking forward, so for example on a four-engine aircraft such as the Boeing 747, engine No.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] 1 is on the left side, farthest from the fuselage, while engine No.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] 3 is on the right side nearest to the fuselage.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] In the case of the twin-engine English Electric Lightning, which has two fuselage-mounted jet engines one above the other, engine No.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] 1 is below and to the front of engine No.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] Refineries blend Avgas with tetraethyllead (TEL) to achieve these high octane ratings, a practice that governments no longer permit for gasoline intended for road vehicles.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] The shrinking supply of TEL and the possibility of environmental legislation banning its use have made a search for replacement fuels for general aviation aircraft a priority for pilots’ organizations.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] Model aircraft typically use nitro engines (also known as "glow engines" due to the use of a glow plug) powered by glow fuel, a mixture of methanol, nitromethane, and lubricant.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] Electrically powered model airplanes and helicopters are also commercially available.
[src:combustor/aircraft-engine] Small multicopter UAVs are almost always powered by electricity, but larger gasoline-powered designs are under development.
[src:combustor/combustor] A **combustor** is a component or area of a gas turbine, ramjet, or scramjet engine where combustion takes place.
[src:combustor/combustor] It is also known as a **burner**, **burner can**, **combustion chamber** or **flame holder**.
[src:combustor/combustor] In a gas turbine engine, the *combustor* or combustion chamber is fed high-pressure air by the compression system.
[src:combustor/combustor] The combustor then heats this air at constant pressure as the fuel/air mix burns.
[src:combustor/combustor] As it burns the fuel/air mix heats and rapidly expands.
[src:combustor/combustor] The burned mix is exhausted from the combustor through the nozzle guide vanes to the turbine.
[src:combustor/combustor] In the case of ramjet or scramjet engines, the exhaust is directly fed out through the nozzle.
[src:combustor/combustor] A combustor must contain and maintain stable combustion despite very high air flow rates.
[src:combustor/combustor] To do so combustors are carefully designed to first mix and ignite the air and fuel, and then mix in more air to complete the combustion process.
[src:combustor/combustor] Early gas turbine engines used a single chamber known as a can-type combustor.
[src:combustor/combustor] Today three main configurations exist: can, annular, and cannular (also referred to as can-annular tubo-annular).
[src:combustor/combustor] Afterburners are often considered another type of combustor.
[src:combustor/combustor] Combustors play a crucial role in determining many of an engine's operating characteristics, such as fuel efficiency, levels of emissions, and transient response (the response to changing conditions such as fuel flow and air speed).
[src:combustor/combustor] The objective of the combustor in a gas turbine is to add energy to the system to power the turbines, and produce a high-velocity gas to exhaust through the nozzle in aircraft applications.
[src:combustor/combustor] Advancements in combustor technology focused on several distinct areas; emissions, operating range, and durability.
[src:combustor/combustor] Early jet engines produced large amounts of smoke, so early combustor advances, in the 1950s, were aimed at reducing the smoke produced by the engine.
[src:combustor/combustor] Once smoke was essentially eliminated, efforts turned in the 1970s to reducing other emissions, like unburned hydrocarbons and carbon monoxide (for more details, see § Emissions).
[src:combustor/combustor] The 1970s also saw improvement in combustor durability, as new manufacturing methods improved liner (see § Components) lifetime by nearly 100 times that of early liners.
[src:combustor/combustor] In the 1980s combustors began to improve their efficiency across the whole operating range; combustors tended to be highly efficient (>99%) at full power, but that efficiency dropped off at lower settings.
[src:combustor/combustor] Development over that decade improved efficiencies at lower levels.
[src:combustor/combustor] The 1990s and 2000s saw a renewed focus on reducing emissions, particularly nitrogen oxides.
[src:combustor/combustor] Combustor technology is still being actively researched and advanced, and much modern research focuses on improving the same aspects.
[src:combustor/combustor] The case is the outer shell of the combustor, and is a fairly simple structure.
[src:combustor/combustor] The casing generally requires little maintenance.
[src:combustor/combustor] The case is protected from thermal loads by the air flowing in it, so thermal performance is of limited concern.
[src:combustor/combustor] However, the casing serves as a pressure vessel that must withstand the difference between the high pressures inside the combustor and the lower pressure outside.
[src:combustor/combustor] That mechanical (rather than thermal) load is a driving design factor in the case.
[src:combustor/combustor] The purpose of the diffuser is to slow the high-speed, highly compressed, air from the compressor to a velocity optimal for the combustor.
[src:combustor/combustor] Reducing the velocity results in an unavoidable loss in total pressure, so one of the design challenges is to limit the loss of pressure as much as possible.
[src:combustor/combustor] Furthermore, the diffuser must be designed to limit the flow distortion as much as possible by avoiding flow effects like boundary layer separation.
[src:combustor/combustor] Like most other gas turbine engine components, the diffuser is designed to be as short and light as possible.
[src:combustor/combustor] The liner contains the combustion process and introduces the various airflows (intermediate, dilution, and cooling, see § Air flow paths) into the combustion zone.
[src:combustor/combustor] The liner must be designed and built to withstand extended high-temperature cycles.
[src:combustor/combustor] For that reason liners tend to be made from superalloys like Hastelloy X.
[src:combustor/combustor] Furthermore, even though high-performance alloys are used, the liners must be cooled with air flow.
[src:combustor/combustor] Some combustors also make use of thermal barrier coatings.
[src:combustor/combustor] In general, there are two main types of liner cooling; film cooling and transpiration cooling.
[src:combustor/combustor] Film cooling works by injecting (by one of several methods) cool air from outside of the liner to just inside of the liner.
[src:combustor/combustor] This creates a thin film of cool air that protects the liner, reducing the temperature at the liner from around 1800 kelvins (K) to around 830 K, for example.
[src:combustor/combustor] The other type of liner cooling, transpiration cooling, is a more modern approach that uses a porous material for the liner.
[src:combustor/combustor] The porous liner allows a small amount of cooling air to pass through it, providing cooling benefits similar to film cooling.
[src:combustor/combustor] The two primary differences are in the resulting temperature profile of the liner and the amount of cooling air required.
[src:combustor/combustor] Transpiration cooling results in a much more even temperature profile, as the cooling air is uniformly introduced through pores.
[src:combustor/combustor] Film cooling air is generally introduced through slats or louvers, resulting in an uneven profile where it is cooler at the slat and warmer between the slats.
[src:combustor/combustor] More importantly, transpiration cooling uses much less cooling air (on the order of 10% of total airflow, rather than 20–50% for film cooling).
[src:combustor/combustor] Using less air for cooling allows more to be used for combustion, which is more and more important for high-performance, high-thrust engines.
[src:combustor/combustor] The snout is an extension of the dome (see below) that acts as an air splitter, separating the primary air from the secondary air flows (intermediate, dilution, and cooling air; see § Air flow paths).
[src:combustor/combustor] The dome and swirler are the part of the combustor that the primary air (see § Air flow paths) flows through as it enters the combustion zone.
[src:combustor/combustor] Their role is to generate turbulence in the flow to rapidly mix the air with fuel.
[src:combustor/combustor] Early combustors tended to use *bluff body domes* (rather than swirlers), which used a simple plate to create wake turbulence to mix the fuel and air.
[src:combustor/combustor] Most modern designs, however, are *swirl stabilized* (use swirlers).
[src:combustor/combustor] The swirler establishes a local low pressure zone that forces some of the combustion products to recirculate, creating the high turbulence.
[src:combustor/combustor] However, the higher the turbulence, the higher the pressure loss will be for the combustor, so the dome and swirler must be carefully designed so as not to generate more turbulence than is needed to sufficiently mix the fuel and air.
[src:combustor/combustor] The fuel injector is responsible for introducing fuel to the combustion zone and, along with the swirler (above), is responsible for mixing the fuel and air.
[src:combustor/combustor] There are four primary types of fuel injectors; pressure-atomizing, air blast, vaporizing, and premix/prevaporizing injectors.
[src:combustor/combustor] Pressure atomizing fuel injectors rely on high fuel pressures (as much as 3,400 kilopascals (500 psi)) to atomize the fuel.
[src:combustor/combustor] This type of fuel injector has the advantage of being very simple, but it has several disadvantages.
[src:combustor/combustor] The fuel system must be robust enough to withstand such high pressures, and the fuel tends to be heterogeneously atomized, resulting in incomplete or uneven combustion which has more pollutants and smoke.
[src:combustor/combustor] The second type of fuel injector is the air blast injector.
[src:combustor/combustor] This injector "blasts" a sheet of fuel with a stream of air, atomizing the fuel into homogeneous droplets.
[src:combustor/combustor] This type of fuel injector led to the first smokeless combustors.
[src:combustor/combustor] The air used is just some of the primary air (see § Air flow paths) that is diverted through the injector, rather than the swirler.
[src:combustor/combustor] This type of injector also requires lower fuel pressures than the pressure atomizing type.
[src:combustor/combustor] The vaporizing fuel injector, the third type, is similar to the air blast injector in that primary air is mixed with the fuel as it is injected into the combustion zone.
[src:combustor/combustor] However, the fuel-air mixture travels through a tube within the combustion zone.
[src:combustor/combustor] Heat from the combustion zone is transferred to the fuel-air mixture, vaporizing some of the fuel (mixing it better) before it is combusted.
[src:combustor/combustor] This method allows the fuel to be combusted with less thermal radiation, which helps protect the liner.
[src:combustor/combustor] However, the vaporizer tube may have serious durability problems with low fuel flow within it (the fuel inside of the tube protects the tube from the combustion heat).
[src:combustor/combustor] The premixing/prevaporizing injectors work by mixing or vaporizing the fuel before it reaches the combustion zone.
[src:combustor/combustor] This method allows the fuel to be very uniformly mixed with the air, reducing emissions from the engine.
[src:combustor/combustor] One disadvantage of this method is that fuel may auto-ignite or otherwise combust before the fuel-air mixture reaches the combustion zone.
[src:combustor/combustor] If this happens the combustor can be seriously damaged.
[src:combustor/combustor] Most igniters in gas turbine applications are electrical spark igniters, similar to automotive spark plugs.
[src:combustor/combustor] The igniter needs to be in the combustion zone where the fuel and air are already mixed, but it needs to be far enough upstream so that it is not damaged by the combustion itself.
[src:combustor/combustor] Once the combustion is initially started by the igniter, it is self-sustaining, and the igniter is no longer used.
[src:combustor/combustor] In can-annular and annular combustors (see § Types of combustors), the flame can propagate from one combustion zone to another, so igniters are not needed at each one.
[src:combustor/combustor] In some systems ignition-assist techniques are used.
[src:combustor/combustor] One such method is oxygen injection, where oxygen is fed to the ignition area, helping the fuel easily combust.
[src:combustor/combustor] This is particularly useful in some aircraft applications where the engine may have to restart at high altitude.
[src:combustor/combustor] It is highly compressed air from the high-pressure compressor (often decelerated via the diffuser) that is fed through the main channels in the dome of the combustor and the first set of liner holes.
[src:combustor/combustor] This air is mixed with fuel, and then combusted.
[src:combustor/combustor] Intermediate air is the air injected into the combustion zone through the second set of liner holes (primary air goes through the first set).
[src:combustor/combustor] This air completes the reaction processes, diluting the high concentrations of carbon monoxide (CO) and hydrogen (H2), and also helps cooling down the gases from combustion.
[src:combustor/combustor] Dilution air is air injected through holes in the liner at the end of the combustion chamber to cool the flue gas before it reaches the turbines.
[src:combustor/combustor] The air is carefully used to produce the uniform temperature profile desired in the combustor.
[src:combustor/combustor] However, as turbine blade technology improves, allowing them to withstand higher temperatures, dilution air is used less, allowing the use of more combustion air.
[src:combustor/combustor] Cooling air is air that is injected through small holes in the liner to generate a layer (film) of cool air to protect the liner from the combustion temperatures.
[src:combustor/combustor] The implementation of cooling air has to be carefully designed so it does not directly interact with the combustion air and process.
[src:combustor/combustor] In some cases, as much as 50% of the inlet air is used as cooling air.
[src:combustor/combustor] There are several different methods of injecting this cooling air, and the method can influence the temperature profile that the liner is exposed to (see § Liner).
[src:combustor/combustor] Can combustors are self-contained cylindrical combustion chambers.
[src:combustor/combustor] Each "can" has its own fuel injector, igniter, liner, and casing.
[src:combustor/combustor] The primary air from the compressor is guided into each individual can, where it is decelerated, mixed with fuel, and then ignited.
[src:combustor/combustor] The secondary air also comes from the compressor, where it is fed outside of the liner (inside of which is where the combustion is taking place).
[src:combustor/combustor] The secondary air is then fed, usually through slits in the liner, into the combustion zone to cool the liner via thin film cooling.
[src:combustor/combustor] In most applications, multiple cans are arranged around the central axis of the engine, and their shared exhaust is fed to the turbine(s).
[src:combustor/combustor] Can-type combustors were most widely used in early gas turbine engines, owing to their ease of design and testing (one can test a single can, rather than have to test the whole system).
[src:combustor/combustor] Can-type combustors are easy to maintain, as only a single can needs to be removed, rather than the whole combustion section.
[src:combustor/combustor] Most modern gas turbine engines (particularly for aircraft applications) do not use can combustors, as they often weigh more than alternatives.
[src:combustor/combustor] Additionally, the pressure drop across the can is generally higher than other combustors (on the order of 7%).
[src:combustor/combustor] Most modern engines that use can combustors are turboshafts featuring centrifugal compressors.
[src:combustor/combustor] The next type of combustor is the "can-annular" combustor.
[src:combustor/combustor] Like the can-type combustor, can-annular combustors have discrete combustion zones contained in separate liners with their own fuel injectors.
[src:combustor/combustor] Unlike the can combustor, all the combustion zones share a common ring (annulus) casing.
[src:combustor/combustor] Each combustion zone no longer has to serve as a pressure vessel.
[src:combustor/combustor] The combustion zones can also "communicate" with each other via liner holes or connecting tubes that allow some air to flow circumferentially.
[src:combustor/combustor] The exit flow from the can-annular combustor generally has a more uniform temperature profile, which is better for the turbine section.
[src:combustor/combustor] It also eliminates the need for each chamber to have its own igniter.
[src:combustor/combustor] Once the fire is lit in one or two cans, it can easily spread to and ignite the others.
[src:combustor/combustor] This type of combustor is also lighter than the can type, and has a lower pressure drop (on the order of 6%).
[src:combustor/combustor] However, a can-annular combustor can be more difficult to maintain than a can combustor.
[src:combustor/combustor] Examples of gas turbine engines utilizing a can-annular combustor include both turbojets like the General Electric J79 and turbofans like the Pratt & Whitney TF30 and Rolls-Royce Tay.
[src:combustor/combustor] The final, and most-commonly used type of combustor is the fully annular combustor.
[src:combustor/combustor] Annular combustors do away with the separate combustion zones and simply have a continuous liner and casing in a ring (the annulus).
[src:combustor/combustor] There are many advantages to annular combustors, including more uniform combustion, shorter size (therefore lighter), and less surface area.
[src:combustor/combustor] Additionally, annular combustors tend to have very uniform exit temperatures.
[src:combustor/combustor] They also have the lowest pressure drop of the three designs (on the order of 5%).
[src:combustor/combustor] The annular design is also simpler, although testing generally requires a full size test rig.
[src:combustor/combustor] Engines that use an annular combustor include the CFM International CFM56, the General Electric F110 and the Pratt & Whitney F401.
[src:combustor/combustor] Almost all of the modern gas turbine engines use annular combustors; likewise, most combustor research and development focuses on improving this type.
[src:combustor/combustor] One variation on the standard annular combustor is the *double annular combustor* (DAC).
[src:combustor/combustor] Like an annular combustor, the DAC is a continuous ring without separate combustion zones around the radius.
[src:combustor/combustor] The difference is that the combustor has two combustion zones around the ring; a pilot zone and a main zone.
[src:combustor/combustor] The pilot zone acts like that of a single annular combustor, and is the only zone operating at low power levels.
[src:combustor/combustor] At high power levels, the main zone is used as well, increasing air and mass flow through the combustor.
[src:combustor/combustor] GE's implementation of this type of combustor focuses on reducing NO*x* and CO2 emissions.
[src:combustor/combustor] A good diagram of a DAC is available from Purdue.
[src:combustor/combustor] Extending the same principles as the double annular combustor, triple annular and "multiple annular" combustors have been proposed and even patented.
[src:combustor/combustor] One of the driving factors in modern gas turbine design is reducing emissions, and the combustor is the primary contributor to a gas turbine's emissions.
[src:combustor/combustor] Generally speaking, there are five major types of emissions from gas turbine engines: smoke, carbon dioxide (CO2), carbon monoxide (CO), unburned hydrocarbons (UHC), and nitrogen oxides (NOx).
[src:combustor/combustor] Smoke is primarily mitigated by more evenly mixing the fuel with air.
[src:combustor/combustor] As discussed in the fuel injector section above, modern fuel injectors (such as airblast fuel injectors) evenly atomize the fuel and eliminate local pockets of high fuel concentration.
[src:combustor/combustor] Most modern engines use these types of fuel injectors and are essentially smokeless.
[src:combustor/combustor] Carbon dioxide is a product of the combustion process, and it is primarily mitigated by reducing fuel usage.
[src:combustor/combustor] On average, 1 kg of jet fuel burned produces 3.2 kg of CO2.
[src:combustor/combustor] Carbon dioxide emissions will continue to drop as manufacturers improve the overall efficiency of gas turbine engines.
[src:combustor/combustor] Unburned-hydrocarbon (UHC) and carbon-monoxide (CO) emissions are highly related.
[src:combustor/combustor] UHCs are essentially fuel that was not completely combusted.
[src:combustor/combustor] They are mostly produced at low power levels (where the engine is not burning all the fuel).
[src:combustor/combustor] Much of the UHC content reacts and forms CO within the combustor, which is why the two types of emissions are heavily related.
[src:combustor/combustor] As a result of this close relation, a combustor that is well optimized for CO emissions is inherently well optimized for UHC emissions, so most design work focuses on CO emissions.
[src:combustor/combustor] Carbon monoxide is an intermediate product of combustion, and it is eliminated by oxidation.
[src:combustor/combustor] This process, which consumes the CO, requires a relatively long time ("relatively" is used because the combustion process happens incredibly quickly), high temperatures, and high pressures.
[src:combustor/combustor] This fact means that a low-CO combustor has a long *residence time* (essentially the amount of time the gases are in the combustion chamber).
[src:combustor/combustor] Like CO, Nitrogen oxides (NOx) are produced in the combustion zone.
[src:combustor/combustor] However, unlike CO, it is most produced during the conditions that CO is most consumed (high temperature, high pressure, long residence time).
[src:combustor/combustor] This means that, in general, reducing CO emissions results in an increase in NOx, and vice versa.
[src:combustor/combustor] This fact means that most successful emission reductions require the combination of several methods.
[src:combustor/combustor] An afterburner (or reheat) is an additional component added to some jet engines, primarily those on military supersonic aircraft.
[src:combustor/combustor] Its purpose is to provide a temporary increase in thrust, both for supersonic flight and for takeoff (as the high wing loading typical of supersonic aircraft designs means that take-off speed is very high).
[src:combustor/combustor] On military aircraft the extra thrust is also useful for combat situations.
[src:combustor/combustor] This is achieved by injecting additional fuel into the jet pipe downstream of (i.e.
[src:combustor/combustor] The advantage of afterburning is significantly increased thrust; the disadvantage is its very high fuel consumption and inefficiency, though this is often regarded as acceptable for the short periods during which it is usually used.
[src:combustor/combustor] Jet engines are referred to as operating *wet* when afterburning is being used and *dry* when the engine is used without afterburning.
[src:combustor/combustor] An engine producing maximum thrust wet is at *maximum power* or *max reheat* (this is the maximum power the engine can produce); an engine producing maximum thrust dry is at *military power* or *max dry*.
[src:combustor/combustor] As with the main combustor in a gas turbine, the afterburner has both a case and a liner, serving the same purpose as their main combustor counterparts.
[src:combustor/combustor] One major difference between a main combustor and an afterburner is that the temperature rise is not constrained by a turbine section, therefore afterburners tend to have a much higher temperature rise than main combustors.
[src:combustor/combustor] Another difference is that afterburners are not designed to mix fuel as well as primary combustors, so not all the fuel is burned within the afterburner section.
[src:combustor/combustor] Afterburners also often require the use of flameholders to keep the velocity of the air in the afterburner from blowing the flame out.
[src:combustor/combustor] These are often bluff bodies or "vee-gutters" directly behind the fuel injectors that create localized low-speed flow in the same manner the dome does in the main combustor.
[src:combustor/combustor] Ramjet engines differ in many ways from traditional gas turbine engines, but most of the same principles hold.
[src:combustor/combustor] One major difference is the lack of rotating machinery (a turbine) after the combustor.
[src:combustor/combustor] The combustor exhaust is directly fed to a nozzle.
[src:combustor/combustor] This allows ramjet combustors to burn at a higher temperature.
[src:combustor/combustor] Another difference is that many ramjet combustors do not use liners like gas turbine combustors do.
[src:combustor/combustor] Furthermore, some ramjet combustors are *dump combustors* rather than a more conventional type.
[src:combustor/combustor] Dump combustors inject fuel and rely on recirculation generated by a large change in area in the combustor (rather than swirlers in many gas turbine combustors).
[src:combustor/combustor] That said, many ramjet combustors are also similar to traditional gas turbine combustors, such as the combustor in the ramjet used by the RIM-8 Talos missile, which used a can-type combustor.
[src:combustor/combustor] Scramjet (*supersonic combustion ramjet*) engines present a much different situation for the combustor than conventional gas turbine engines (scramjets are not gas turbines, as they generally have few or no moving parts).
[src:combustor/combustor] While scramjet combustors may be physically quite different from conventional combustors, they face many of the same design challenges, like fuel mixing and flame holding.
[src:combustor/combustor] However, as its name implies, a scramjet combustor must address these challenges in a supersonic flow environment.
[src:combustor/combustor] For example, for a scramjet flying at Mach 5, the air flow entering the combustor would nominally be Mach 2.
[src:combustor/combustor] One of the major challenges in a scramjet engine is preventing shock waves generated by combustor from traveling upstream into the inlet.
[src:combustor/combustor] If that were to happen, the engine may unstart, resulting in loss of thrust, among other problems.
[src:combustor/combustor] To prevent this, scramjet engines tend to have an isolator section (see image) immediately ahead of the combustion zone.
